x Club, Hasty Pudding."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Walter Camp named him All-American halfback in 1909","body":"Wayland Manning Minot was a consensus All-American halfback at Harvard in 1909, selected by Walter Camp — the father of American football. He played on the 1910 Harvard team under coach Percy Haughton that allowed only five points all season, a remarkable defensive record that helped make Harvard the national power of that era. He also earned a varsity letter in baseball as an outfielder.","number":1},{"header":"He crashed his car into a Charles River","body":"In January 1933, Minot was involved in a late-night accident on the Charles River Dam Bridge. His car crashed into a drawbridge and burned. A passenger died.","number":2},{"header":"He was the first commander of the 771st","body":"After WWI service in France as a Major in the AEF Field Artillery, Minot returned to the Army Reserve. He was promoted to Lieutenant Colonel in 1932 and became the first commander of the 771st Tank Destroyer Battalion when it was activated on December 15, 1941 — two weeks after Pearl Harbor. He led the early training stages but was forced to leave the unit in 1942 due to illness, never deploying with the battalion he had formed.","number":3}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Major Wayland Manning Minot","first_name":"Wayland","last_name":"Minot","middle_name":"Manning","title":"Major","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/93/Wayland_Minot_%28Harvard_Crimson_football_player%29_circa_1910.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"wayland-minot-1889"},"X00749":{"id":"X00749","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant"